Tags: astro/physics, astroparticles, Computer, Cosmology, infographics, PhD&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Recently I am interested in &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_graphics" target="_blank" title="Infographics on wikipedia"&gt;infographics&lt;/a&gt; (check also &lt;a href="http://www.coolinfographics.com/" target="_blank" title="Coolinfographics"&gt;this&lt;/a&gt;) and if it can help communicating science. There are also two interesting projects related to this, &lt;a href="http://prezi.com/" target="_blank" title="Prezi homepage"&gt;Prezi&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://sozi.baierouge.fr/wiki/en:welcome" target="_blank" title="Sozi homepage"&gt;Sozi&lt;/a&gt;. I'm not an artist but I want to try to change my way of communicating and to save lectures notes. This is my first attempt, the first lesson of the Astroparticles course for PhD students! It is not really "graphic", but it's my first step!:P&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/infographics-attempts.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>astro/physics</category><category>astroparticles</category><category>Cosmology</category><category>infographics</category><category>PhD</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/infographics-attempts.html</guid><pubDate>Mon, 23 Apr 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>PhD question #4: calculate the value of M*</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/phd-question-4-calculate-the-value-of-m.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Some post ago &lt;a href="/posts/phd-question-1-m.html"&gt;I've written about M*&lt;/a&gt;, the typical non-linear mass collapsing at the redshift we are considering. Now I have to find a value for it.     &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/phd-question-4-calculate-the-value-of-m.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>astro/physics</category><category>code</category><category>Computer</category><category>Cosmology</category><category>N-body</category><category>PhD</category><category>simulation</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/phd-question-4-calculate-the-value-of-m.html</guid><pubDate>Tue, 03 Apr 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Never never never...</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/never-never-never.html</link><description>&lt;p&gt;... never forget that the result of the "integer" division 4/3 is equal to 1 instead of 1.333333333... in, I think, almost all programming languages. This is because it's the division between two integers. Only in Python3 it will give what we expect. It's a detail, and I usually remember it and I write 4./3 (4. is of type "float"), but this time I forget it, and I have obtained wrong results for a week. I didn't understand why and I've searched any possible complex and deep explanation. But it was one of the most simple and stupid errors!:P&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Moreover, always check every new result with the older ones. I didn't do this, and I find strange results after two months of computing. Next time, remember to check EVERY new results!&lt;/p&gt;</description><category>astro/physics</category><category>Cosmology</category><category>N-body</category><category>PhD</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/never-never-never.html</guid><pubDate>Tue, 03 Apr 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>PhD question #3: Monte Carlo Markov chain</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/phd-question-3-monte-carlo-markov-chain.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;After &lt;a href="http://www.brunettoziosi.eu/blog/wordpress/phd-question-1-latexm_latex/" target="_blank" title="PhD question #1: M*"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://www.brunettoziosi.eu/blog/wordpress/phd-question-2-spherical-collapse/" target="_blank" title="PhD question #2: spherical collapse"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, in thisp post I write about the Monte Carlo Markov chain. This post is the Wordpress transposition of a page in my private and local Mediawiki installation, so maybe has not a perfect structure and look&amp;amp;feel. Also, the Latex formulas embedded in &lt;a href="http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/MediaWiki" target="_blank" title="Mediawiki homepage"&gt;Mediawiki&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://wordpress.com/" target="_blank" title="Wordpress homepage"&gt;Wordpress&lt;/a&gt; look horrible.  &lt;br&gt;
Most of this post is made by paragraphs from &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page" target="_blank" title="Wikipedia homepage"&gt;Wikipedia&lt;/a&gt; and from &lt;a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/0712.3028" target="_blank" title="Licia Verde's article page"&gt;A practical guide to Basic Statistical Techniques for Data Analysis in Cosmology&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="http://icc.ub.edu/~liciaverde/Home%20Page.html" target="_blank" title="Licia Verde homepage"&gt;Licia Verde&lt;/a&gt; that I rearranged or try to explain and summarize.    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Essentially you can think a Markov chain as a set of states of physical system, or a series of values, depending on some parameters, in which every step/status depends only on the present status and not on the past. A Monte Carlo Markov chain is a Markov chain that proceeds trying random steps and tends to converge to an equilibrium that should be the best set of parameters we are looking for.  &lt;br&gt;
To improve performances and precision usually more chains are used, starting from different and well-separated points, for a single estimation and a convergence criterion define when to stop.  &lt;br&gt;
The steady state, or the equilibrium distribution, if it exists, roughly is the combination of parameters, o the vector for the probabilities to be in one status, that emerge to be constant in the long term. This means that if the system (the chain) at some time has a probability vector $q$ for the next status, it will have probability vector $q$ forever. $q$ is an eigenvector of the transition matrix with eingenvalue 1.    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/phd-question-3-monte-carlo-markov-chain.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>astro/physics</category><category>Computer</category><category>Cosmology</category><category>data_reduction</category><category>markov_chain</category><category>MCMC</category><category>PhD</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/phd-question-3-monte-carlo-markov-chain.html</guid><pubDate>Thu, 15 Mar 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Learning C from simulations, #3: C horrors!</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/learning-c-from-simulations-3-c-horrors.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Yeah, this is post #3! Post #2 is "work in progress" and it will be on FFTs!    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today I was trying to understand what this piece of code do:    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;for&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;i&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;i&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;Nmesh&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;/&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;i&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;++&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
